I have successfully identified and fixed the bug in the TarUtils.java file. Here's a summary of what I did:

## Problem Analysis
The bug was in the `formatLongOctalOrBinaryBytes` method in the `TarUtils.java` file. The issue was with the control flow when deciding between formatting as octal or binary:

1. When `length < 9`, the code would call `formatLongBinary`
2. Regardless of the condition, it would always call `formatBigIntegerBinary` afterward
3. This caused incorrect behavior because both formatters were being called when `length >= 9`

## The Fix
I changed the control structure from:
```java
if (length < 9) {
    formatLongBinary(value, buf, offset, length, negative);
}
formatBigIntegerBinary(value, buf, offset, length, negative);
```

To:
```java
if (length < 9) {
    formatLongBinary(value, buf, offset, length, negative);
} else {
    formatBigIntegerBinary(value, buf, offset, length, negative);
}
```

This ensures that only one of the two formatting methods is called based on the length parameter.

## Verification
- The triggering test `org.apache.commons.compress.archivers.tar.TarUtilsTest::testRoundTripOctalOrBinary8` now passes
- Related tests continue to pass
- The code compiles successfully

The fix is contained in the `blind_fix.patch` file that I generated.

